\title{CensusACS: American Community Survey aggregates}
\description{
Retrieves American Community Survey (ACS) estimates — income, employment, and
demographics for every US geography — as a wide table, one row per geography and
one column per requested variable.
}
\details{
ACS uses the standard \code{get}/\code{for}/\verb{in} grammar. You choose the variables (up to
50 per call; e.g. \code{"B19013_001E"} for median household income, \code{"NAME"} for the
geography label) and the geography (\code{geo_for}, e.g. \code{"county:*"}), supplying any
required parent geographies in \code{geo_in} (e.g. \code{"state:06"}). The result is a
dynamic-width \link[=census_shapes]{AcsTable}: estimate (\verb{*E}) and margin (\verb{*M})
columns are numeric, annotation (\verb{*EA}/\verb{*MA}) and code columns character.

Two datasets: \code{acs1} (1-year, geographies of at least 65,000 population) and
\code{acs5} (5-year, every geography down to block group). \strong{Each survey year is its
own dataset} — the vintage is the \code{year} argument, and there is no \code{time}
predicate (unlike the EITS family). Note the Bureau did not release standard
1-year estimates for 2020.

Geography validation: with \code{validate_geo = TRUE} (default), the method makes a
keyless pre-flight fetch of the dataset's geography metadata and checks the
\code{requires} chain — a wildcard child (\verb{county:*}) may omit its parents, a
specific child (\code{county:037}) may not. Set \code{validate_geo = FALSE} to skip the
pre-flight (as \code{\link[=census_backfill_acs]{census_backfill_acs()}} does, validating once).

Inherits from \link{CensusBase}; all methods honour the \code{async} flag.
\subsection{Point-in-time note}{

ACS is annual with a long lag (1-year ~9 months, 5-year ~15 months) and is a
structural/reference series, not a time signal — see \link{CensusEconomicIndicators}
for the vintage discipline that applies to the revisable economic series.
}
